body:
Renaming it to something much longer and more cumbersome, like `unrwap_or_fail` or `unrwap_or_abort` depending on the outcome of the "renaiming fail!" discussion would do much more to discourage use.

@huonw I'm in agreement with you that this should be used less frequently, but that doesn't mean that it isn't used a lot now and that doesn't mean that this isn't a huge breaking change for marginal benefit, especially with an unclear and confusing name like `assert` replacing it.

I also echo @kballard s concern in that this process seemed a bit opaque - there was lot discussion but mostly disagreement among the community, and to see something this common changed almost silently is pretty weird.

@huonw: Lots of functions are partial anyway. Giving them special names for that reason makes no sense. `unwrap` is really not that special compared to other functions that might also fail.

I say, keep `unwrap` as is. Assume it might fail, just like every other function not explicitly declared non-failing.

Edit: Sorry "lots of functions are partial".

The more I think about what an assertion means, the more that I think that `unwrap` is fundamentally an assertion, and should be treated as such. Assert means "I say this value is something, or else crash." That's what `unwrap()` does. There is little difference between (C code):

``` c
int foo(char *format )
{
    assert( format != NULL );
    // other stuff
```

and

``` rust
fn foo(format: Option<String>) -> int {
    let format = format.unwrap();
```

With the name changed, this becomes

``` rust
fn foo(format: Option<String>) -> int {
    let format = format.assert();
```

Comparing:

```
    assert( format != NULL );
    let format = format.assert();
```

Other than that one is a function and one is the method, feels very, very close to me.

Note that also, the reason that `assert` doesn't need to return a value in C is because there's no concept of `Option` to begin with. But in Rust, combined with shadowing, this makes a lot of sense.

@steveklabnik: `format.assert();` does not convey that a value is being unwrapped. It appears to be a short-hand for:

```
if format.is_none() {
    fail!("assertion failed");
}
```

The term `assert` already has another well-known meaning in programming.

@pcwalton Agreed, this change wouldn't pass a democratic process.

However, I'm not sure if that is a good thing. If so many people are opposed to the change, maybe it would be better to reconsider?

There is no cost associated with admitting an error, but there is value in correcting it.

@pnkfelix I apologize for my last comment (and maybe old ones), if you think it's "particularly rude". I'll make sure never leave rude comments, I promise. So don't ban me or put me into the blacklist or something else, please! I still want to be active in the Rust community. As a note, I did contribute to Rust source, docs and issues in the past, e.g. the latest #16448 / #16928.

The following is some explain for my last comment (both -1 has its reason in original comment already):

The core team posted on [discuss](http://discuss.rust-lang.org/t/settling-some-key-naming-conventions/269) first and quickly made decision only two days later without public [meeting report](https://github.com/rust-lang/meeting-minutes/pull/2) (which was delayed merging for about two weeks). Both the post and the api meeting did not explicitly claim renaming `.unwrap()` to `.assert()`. They didn't post on reddit, which is definitely much more popular than discuss.rust-lang.org. As you have seen, many many people were [surprised](http://www.reddit.com/r/rust/comments/2dbg3j/hm_unwrap_is_being_renamed_to_assert/) by renaming `unwrap` to `assert`. This was the reason why I said "(make this decision and discuss it) in the corner" and "opaque process" in my last comment. I did seen some core members explain "why this is not opaque process" before, but that's not convincing IMO.

@liigo I don't think pnkfelix has the power to "ban you" or "put you into the blacklist." Even if he did, I doubt it would be exercised. As long as you're a helpful member of the community, people will be happy to have you around. In particular, I don't think you need to justify yourself based on your contributions - those actions speak for themselves.

However, everyone participating in this thread is well-aware of all of the points you brought up: they're the core issue at hand, and the reason for nikomatsakis' resolution above. So you're not adding anything to the discussion by simply restating/summarizing the core controversy. Especially in this case - where the issue has been acknowledged, and a long-term solution agreed upon by the core team.

So pnkfenix has a point here: developers dedicate time and energy to reading your posts and placing them in the context of an entire issue. The bare minimum respect you can have for others' time is to read the threads carefully before commenting. This makes the best possible use of everyone's time, including your own, since you won't have to deal with people complaining when you want to get your opinion heard.
